SN  - 0263-2241
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/j.measurement.2025.118482
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S026322412501841X
KW  - Improved minimum controlled recursive average
KW  - Temporal convolutional network
KW  - Complete ensemble empirical mode decomposition
KW  - Acoustic fault diagnosis
KW  - Rotating machinery
KW  - Hydroelectric generating unit
AB  - This study explores the intelligent diagnosis of mechanical faults by analyzing acoustic signals. It tackles challenges such as intricate frequency components, substantial noise energy with broad bandwidth, and complex pattern recognition in mechanical fault acoustic signals. To address these issues, a novel diagnostic method is proposed. Initially, the study presents the Improved Minimum Controlled Recursive Average − Improved Spectral Subtraction Algorithm (IMCRA-ISSA) for denoising. This algorithm facilitates real-time re-estimation of the signal power spectrum and adaptively refines the spectral subtraction operator based on the estimation outcomes. This results in an adaptive spectral subtraction technique. Subsequently, the denoised acoustic signals are examined using the Complete Ensemble Empirical Mode Decomposition with Adaptive Noise (CEEMDAN) algorithm to derive multiscale intrinsic empirical mode functions that serve as effective inputs for the deep learning model. Additionally, a Convolutional Neural Network − Temporal Convolutional Network (CNN-TCN) diagnostic model is developed to identify mechanical fault signals under varying noise levels and operational conditions. This method is applied to Kaplan-type hydroelectric generating units, a typical category of electro-hydraulic systems that integrate hydraulic turbines with electric generators and are widely deployed in hydropower stations. The system successfully identifies typical fault sounds under realistic operational conditions. Comparative analysis of rotor system fault signals across different SNRs reveals that the IMCRA-ISSA method proficiently denoises mechanical fault signals within an SNR range of −20 dB to 10 dB, delivering optimal performance. It effectively resolves the issue of substantial broadband noise interference encountered when processing the acoustic signals of hydroelectric units. The CNN-TCN model not only excels in extracting the spatial features of the acoustic signals but also efficiently captures their temporal dependencies, surpassing other combined models in experimental evaluations. The proposed method effectively surmounts the challenges of denoising, filtering, and pattern recognition of rotating machinery fault acoustic signals amidst strong noise interference, demonstrating considerable engineering application value.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The new role of sustainable hydropower in flexible energy systems and its technical evolution through innovation and digitalization
AU  - Vagnoni, Elena
AU  - Gezer, Dogan
AU  - Anagnostopoulos, Ioannis
AU  - Cavazzini, Giovanna
